Actually it's some sort of policy against over-beaten egg whites. You can either use an expensive copper egg-beating bowl, which helps form more stable beaten whites that are less prone to breaking and weeping (the copper interferes with too-strong sulfur bonds from forming). You can add a little cream of tartar to the whites, an acid that also prevents those sulfur bonds from forming.

Why do you think the folding part is important?

Kind of. That gentle folding is key, since you want to keep as many of the tiny air bubbles trapped in the beaten whites as you can. The more you mix, and the more vigorously you do it, the more air bubbles you'll lose. Once in the oven, those air bubbles will expand as gases and steam inflate them. That's what causes a soufflé to rise, and really, there's no stopping it—your beaten whites will contain air bubbles and those air bubbles will expand, and when they do your soufflé will push higher and higher in its baking dish.

The temperature will highly affect the consistency of your soufflée
Quiz time: What happens if you choose a temperature that's a bit higher than indicated here and what happens if you choose one that is a bit lower?
it will be flat or rise too high

You're right! The hotter the oven, the more quickly and fully the soufflé will rise, and the faster it will brown and set on the outside. But the soufflé is also more likely to remain runny in the center, since it'd come close to burning on the outside if you were to leave it long enough to cook through to the center. If you like a fully set soufflé, a lower temperature might be your preference.
